SIMPLE: economical
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Economical
<hw>E`co*nom"ic*al</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧conomique</ets>, L. <ets>oeconomicus</ets> orderly,
methodical, Gr. <?/ economical. See <er>Economy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Pertaining to the household; domestic.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In this
<xex>economical</xex> misfortune [of ill-assorted matrimony.]⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Relating to domestic economy, or to the management
of household affairs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And doth employ her <qex>economic</qex> art⟦br⟧
And busy care, her household to preserve.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Managing with frugality; guarding against waste or
unnecessary expense; careful and frugal in management and in
expenditure; -- said of character or habits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Just rich enough, with <qex>economic</qex> care,⟦br⟧
To save a pittance.</q> <rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Managed with frugality; not marked with waste or
extravagance; using the minimum of time or effort or resources required
for effectiveness; frugal; -- said of acts; saving; <as>as, an
<ex>economical</ex> use of money or of time; an <ex>economic</ex> use of
home heating oil</as>.</def> <wns>[wns=3]</wns>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>of or pertaining to the national or regional
economy; relating to political economy; relating to the means of living,
or the resources and wealth of a country; relating to the production or
consumption of goods and services of a nation or region; <as>as,
<ex>economic</ex> growth; <ex>economic</ex> purposes;
<ex>economical</ex> truths; an <ex>economic</ex>
downturn.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These matters <qex>economical</qex> and political.</q> <rj><qau>J.
C. Shairp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was no <qex>economical</qex> distress in England to prompt
the enterprises of colonization.</q> <rj><qau>Palfrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Economic</qex> questions, such as money, usury, taxes, lands,
and the employment of the people.</q> <rj><qau>H. C.
Baird.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Regulative; relating to the adaptation of means to
an end.</def> <rj><au>Grew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>of or pertaining to economics.</def>
<illu><ex>economic</ex> theory</illu>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>profitable. Opposite of <ant>uneconomic</ant>.</def>
<wns>[wns=4]</wns>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>avoiding waste; <as>as, an <ex>economical</ex>
meal</as>. Opposite of <ant>wasteful</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> frugal, scotch, sparing, stinting,
thrifty.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Economical</xex> is the usual form when meaning
frugal, saving; <xex>economic</xex> is the form commonly used when
meaning pertaining to the management of a household, or of public
affairs.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Economically</ent>⟦br⟧
